workflow.name: Public Webhook Relay
workflow.description:
## Disclaimer
This template only works on n8n local instances!

## How it Works
This workflow allows you to to receive webhooks from the public web and have your local workflow catch them, without any remote proxy. It is very useful for running quick tests without exposing your dev server. All you have to do is activate the workflow and use the public address as defined below.

## Set up steps
If you use the default key-value storage, there are only three steps:
1. Install the *@horka.tv/n8n-nodes-storage-kv* community node
2. Put your n8n workflow address in **Local Webhook Address**
3. Activate the workflow and, from *Executions*, note down your public webhook token from the inputs to **Get Latest Requests**. 

You can now use https://webhook.site/[YOUR TOKEN] as a webhook destination, to receive webhook requests from the public web.

# Public Webhook Relay
## How it Works
Utilizes webhook.site to receive public webhook requests and relays them to your local n8n workflow

## How to Use
- To use with local key-value store:
 Go to settings > community nodes and enter ```@horka.tv/n8n-nodes-storage-kv``` to install the key-value store node
- To use with a different storage method:
 Replace the four key-value nodes with a temporary storage option of your choice (Airtable, Notion, Firebase, etc). This is required to save data between runs.
- Set **Schedule Trigger** with a polling interval (default is every 10 seconds).
- Set your local workflow address in Local Webhook Address.

## How to Test
- Set the workflow to *Active*.
- After workflow executes at least once, you can check the input to **Get Latest Requests** for your auth token.
- Run this command: ```curl -X POST -H "Content-Type: application/json" -d '{"foo":"bar"}'  https://webhook.site/[THE AUTH TOKEN YOU JUST GOT]```
- Now check **Executions** and confirm that the workflow ran all the way to the end. Confirm in **Unprocessed Requests** that your data was retrieved (data[0].content should be equal to {"foo":"bar"})
- Now check your other local workflow and confirm that it was triggered with the correct data packet ```{"foo":"bar"}```.
- *You're done!*

## Caveats
At present, the relay expects a POST with form/json data. If you wish to relay raw data or GET requests, please alter the **Unprocessed Requests** and **POST to n8n** nodes accordingly.

data.details:
The IF node can be used to implement binary conditional logic in your workflow. You can set up one-to-many conditions to evaluate each item of data being inputted into the node. That data will either evaluate to TRUE or FALSE and route out of the node accordingly.

This node has multiple types of conditions: Bool, String, Number, and Date & Time.
